  <div class="fd-content">
    <h2>Types of Fixed Deposit Schemes</h2>

    <p>
      Fixed Deposits are not one-size-fits-all. Banks and institutions offer
      multiple FD variants based on how interest is paid, liquidity needs,
      and flexibility requirements.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Bank Fixed Deposits:</strong> Standard FDs with flexible tenures and predictable returns.</li>

      <li><strong>Post Office Fixed Deposits:</strong> Government-backed FDs known for safety and stability.</li>

      <li><strong>Tax-Saving Fixed Deposits:</strong> 5-year lock-in FDs offering tax benefits under Section 80C.</li>

      <li><strong>Senior Citizen Fixed Deposits:</strong> Higher interest rates for individuals aged 60+.</li>

      <li><strong>Cumulative Fixed Deposits:</strong> Interest compounds and is paid at maturity — ideal for growth.</li>

      <li><strong>Non-Cumulative Fixed Deposits:</strong> Periodic payouts — suitable for regular income needs.</li>

      <li><strong>Flexi Fixed Deposits:</strong> Savings + FD combo with automatic conversion of excess balance.</li>

      <li><strong>Sweep-in Fixed Deposits:</strong> Excess savings swept into FD while allowing easy withdrawals.</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="text-muted">
      Choosing the right FD depends on whether your priority is growth, income, or liquidity.
    </p>
  </div>

